logins <- sapply(repository_info, function(item) item$owner$login)

get_owner_details <- function(owner) {
  owner_response <- gh("https://api.github.com/users/{login}", login=owner)
  data.frame(
    login = owner,
    public_repos = owner_response$public_repos,
    created_at = owner_response$created_at,
    followers = owner_response$followers
  )
}

owners_df = map_df(logins, get_owner_details) %>% arrange(desc(public_repos)) %>% distinct()

Table 3: Recently closed issue in each repository.

# Function to fetch closed issues for a repository
get_closed_issues <- function(full_name) {
  issues <- gh(sprintf("/repos/%s/issues", full_name), state = "closed")
  return(issues)
}

# Function to find the most recently closed issue
find_most_recently_closed_issue <- function(issues) {
  if (length(issues) == 0) {
    return(NULL)
  }
  most_recent_issue <- issues[[1]]
  for (issue in issues) {
    if (issue$closed_at > most_recent_issue$closed_at) {
      most_recent_issue <- issue
    }
  }
  return(most_recent_issue)
}

result_df <- data.frame(full_name = character(),
                        title = character(),
                        created_at = character(),
                        closed_at = character(),
                        days_to_close = integer())

# Iterate over each repository
for (repo in repository_info) {
  issues <- get_closed_issues(repo$full_name)

  # Find the most recently closed issue
  most_recent_issue <- find_most_recently_closed_issue(issues)

  # Extract required information and store in data frame
  if (!is.null(most_recent_issue)) {
    result_df <- rbind(result_df,
                       data.frame(full_name = repo$full_name,
                                  title = most_recent_issue$title,
                                  created_at = most_recent_issue$created_at,
                                  closed_at = most_recent_issue$closed_at,
                                  days_to_close = as.integer(difftime(most_recent_issue$closed_at, most_recent_issue$created_at, units = "days"))))
  }
}


kable(head(result_df, n = 10), format = "html",
      align = "c", caption = "Most recently closed issue in each repository") |> kable_styling(full_width = TRUE, bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed", "responsive"), position = "center")

Creating Plots :

First plot: A bar plot of top 5 other topics that most frequently co-occur with the selected topic.

item <- repository_info
topics <- lapply(item, function(repo) repo$topics)

topics <- unlist(topics)
other_topics <- topics[topics != 'deep-learning']

topic_freq <- table(other_topics)

#print(topics)
top_5_topics <- names(sort(topic_freq, decreasing = TRUE))[1:5]

top_5_topics_data <- data.frame(topic = top_5_topics, count = topic_freq[top_5_topics])

ggplot(top_5_topics_data, aes(x = reorder(topic, -count.Freq), y = count.Freq, fill = topic)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    x = "Topic",
    y = "Frequency",
    title = "Top 5 other topics similar to Deep-Learning"
    ) +
  theme_clean() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1), 
        plot.title = element_text(color = "black", size = 12, hjust = 0.5),
        axis.text = element_text(face = "bold", size = 10),
        axis.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 10)
        )

Insights :

The plot illustrates that “machine-learning” is the most prevalent topic that co-occurs with “Deep-Learning,” followed by “python,” which ranks second in frequency, and “pytorch,” which is third. Other topics like “data-science” and “tensorflow” have shown the same frequency as each other.

Second plot : A line chart showing the trend of the number of repos created each year.

# Extract the creation dates of the repositories
creation_dates <- repos_info |>
  select(created_at)

#year
creation_dates$year <- as.integer(substr(creation_dates$created_at, 1, 4))


repo_counts <- creation_dates |>
  group_by(year) |>
  summarise(num_repos = n())

all_years <- data.frame(year = min(repo_counts$year):max(repo_counts$year))
repo_counts <- all_years %>%
  left_join(repo_counts, by = "year") %>%
  mutate(num_repos = ifelse(is.na(num_repos), 0, num_repos))  # Replace NA counts with 0


ggplot(repo_counts, aes(x = year, y = num_repos)) + 
  geom_line(color = "blue") +
  labs(
    x = "Year",
    y = "Number of repositories created",
    title = "Trend of repositories created each year"
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = unique(repo_counts$year)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, max(repo_counts$num_repos), by = 8)) +
  theme(
    axis.text = element_text(face = "bold", size = 13),
    axis.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 13),
    plot.title = element_text(color = "blue", face = "bold", size = 16, hjust = 0.5) 
  )

Insights :

The above plot shows that highest number of repositories were created in 2017.
